    <div class="container">
        <h1>Python Variables</h1>
        <p>
            <strong>1. Explain what are variables in Python</strong><br>
            In Python, variables are used to store data. They act as containers for values, allowing you to manipulate and work with data in your programs.
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>2. How to create a variable in Python</strong><br>
            You can create a variable in Python by assigning a value to a name. For example:
            <code>my_variable = 42</code>
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>3. Casting the type of variable</strong><br>
            Python allows you to change the data type of a variable. This is known as type casting. For example, to convert a number to a string:
            <code>num = 42</code><br>
            <code>num_str = str(num)</code>
        </p>

        <p>
            <strong>4. Explain about case sensitivity of variables in Python</strong><br>
            Python is case-sensitive, meaning variable names like <code>my_var</code> and <code>my_Var</code> are treated as different variables. It's essential to use consistent casing when referencing variables.
        </p>
    </div>
